cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.DC, cs.MM. 

The paper deals with the problem of distributed compression of correlated sources with action-dependent joint distribution, which is a problem in information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses a network coding setup, which involves communication networks, making cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) another likely sub-category. The paper also studies the implications of actions on the achievable rates, which is related to decision-making and control, making cs.SI (Systems and Control) a possible sub-category. The paper also provides a complete single-letter characterization of the set of achievable rates, which is related to algorithms and complexity, making cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper investigates two binary examples, which is related to multimedia, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category.
